# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: casting
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:casting/70s] The **70s** was a decade that ran from January 1, AD 70, to December 31, AD 79.
[src:casting/70s] As the decade began, the First Jewish–Roman War continued: In AD 70, the Romans besieged and sacked Jerusalem and destroyed the Second Temple.
[src:casting/70s] After this major victory, the Romans continued to clear pockets of Jewish resistance, with the final stronghold taken being Masada (73).
[src:casting/70s] The Flavian dynasty, which included emperors Vespasian and Titus, ruled the empire during this decade.
[src:casting/70s] During their reign, the Romans faced military challenges from various sources, including clashes with British and Germanic tribes.
[src:casting/70s] However, the Romans were largely successful in defeating these tribes, expanding their territories and consolidating their power.
[src:casting/70s] Following the death of Vologases I in 78, Parthia saw internal conflict as Vologases II and Pacorus II competed for the throne.
[src:casting/70s] In China, the Han–Xiongnu War was re-invigorated, with the Han defeating the Northern Xiongnu in the Battle of Yiwulu (73).
[src:casting/70s] In 75, Emperor Ming of Han died, being succeeded by Emperor Zhang: the reign of these two emperors is considered to have been a golden age.
[src:casting/70s] The destruction of Jerusalem and the Second Temple during the First Jewish–Roman War marked a major turning point in Jewish history.
[src:casting/70s] The loss of mother-city and temple necessitated a reshaping of Jewish culture to ensure its survival.
[src:casting/70s] Judaism's Temple-based sects, including the priesthood and the Sadducees, diminished in importance.
[src:casting/70s] A new form of Judaism that became known as Rabbinic Judaism developed out of Pharisaic school and, centuries later, eventually became the mainstream form of the religion.
[src:casting/70s] Many followers of Jesus of Nazareth also survived the city's destruction.
[src:casting/70s] They spread his teachings across the Roman Empire, giving rise to the new religion of Christianity.
[src:casting/70s] In the autumn of 79, Mount Vesuvius violently spewed forth a deadly cloud of super-heated tephra and gases to a height of 33 km (21 mi), ejecting molten rock, pulverized pumice and hot ash.
[src:casting/70s] The event destroyed several towns and minor settlements in the area, at the time part of the Roman Empire.
[src:casting/70s] Pompeii and Herculaneum, obliterated and buried underneath massive pyroclastic surges and ashfall deposits, are the most famous examples.
[src:casting/70s] The total population of both cities was over 20,000.
[src:casting/70s] The remains of over 1,500 people have been found at Pompeii and Herculaneum so far, although the total death toll from the eruption remains unknown.
[src:casting/70s] The period also saw significant architectural and engineering accomplishments, such as the construction of the Colosseum in Rome.
[src:casting/70s] In 75, Vespasian erected a colossal statue of Apollo, begun under Nero, and he dedicated a stage of the theatre of Marcellus.
[src:casting/70s] Valerius Flaccus wrote the *Argonautica*, an epic poem.
[src:casting/70s] Pliny the Elder composed the 10-volume *Natural History*, covering topics including astronomy, mathematics, geography, ethnography, anthropology, human physiology, zoology, botany, agriculture, horticulture, pharmacology, mining, mineralogy, sculpture, art, and precious stones.
[src:casting/70s] Manning (2008) tentatively estimates the world population in AD 70 to have been 250 million.
[src:casting/80s] The **80s** was a decade that ran from January 1, AD 80, to December 31, AD 89.
[src:casting/80s] As the decade began, the Parthian Empire was in a phase of division until Pacorus II managed to consolidate his rule, eliminating the two rival contenders for his throne: Vologases II in AD 80 and Artabanus III in AD 81.
[src:casting/80s] Domitian became Roman emperor in AD 81: The military campaigns undertaken during his reign were generally defensive in nature, as the Emperor rejected the idea of expansionist warfare.
[src:casting/80s] His most significant military contribution was the development of the Limes Germanicus, which encompassed a vast network of roads, forts and watchtowers constructed along the Rhine river to defend the Empire.
[src:casting/80s] Nevertheless, several important wars were fought in Gaul, against the Chatti, and across the Danube frontier against the Suebi, the Sarmatians, and the Dacians (see Domitian's Dacian War).
[src:casting/80s] In northern Britain, the Romans defeated local tribes in the Battle of Mons Graupius (AD 83).
[src:casting/80s] In China, the Han–Xiongnu War continued, with the Battle of the Altai Mountains (AD 89) bringing the Northern Xiongnu to the brink of collapse.
[src:casting/80s] The death of Emperor Zhang of Han ended a golden age.
[src:casting/80s] In spring of AD 80, a fire broke out in Rome and burned large parts of the city for three days and three nights.
[src:casting/80s] Emperor Titus personally compensated for the damaged regions.
[src:casting/80s] According to Suetonius, a plague also broke out during the fire.
[src:casting/80s] The nature of the disease, however, and the death toll are unknown.
[src:casting/80s] Manning (2008) tentatively estimates the world population in AD 80 to have been 250 million.
[src:casting/angle-plate] An **angle plate** is a work holding device used as a fixture in metalworking, including grinding.
[src:casting/angle-plate] Angle plates are used to hold workpieces square to the table during marking out operations.
[src:casting/angle-plate] **Adjustable angle plates** are also available for workpieces that need to be inclined, usually towards a milling cutter.
[src:casting/angle-plate] Angle plates are made from high-quality material (generally spheroidal cast iron) that has been stabilized to prevent further movement or distortion.
[src:casting/angle-plate] Slotted holes or "T" bolt slots are machined into the surfaces to enable the secure attachment or clamping of workpieces to the plate, and the plate to the worktable.
[src:casting/angle-plate] The knee type angle plate is typically used for grinding work.
[src:casting/anodizing] The process is called *anodizing* because the part to be treated forms the anode electrode of an electrolytic cell.
[src:casting/anodizing] Anodizing increases resistance to corrosion and wear, and provides better adhesion for paint primers and glues than bare metal does.
[src:casting/anodizing] Anodic films can also be used for several cosmetic effects, either with thick porous coatings that can absorb dyes or with thin coatings whose color is due to thin film interference.
[src:casting/anodizing] Anodizing is also used to prevent galling of threaded components and to make dielectric films for electrolytic capacitors.
[src:casting/anodizing] Anodic films are most commonly applied to protect aluminium alloys, although processes also exist for titanium, zinc, magnesium, niobium, zirconium, hafnium, and tantalum.
[src:casting/anodizing] Carbon flakes or nodules in iron or steel with high carbon content (high-carbon steel, cast iron) may cause an electrolytic potential and interfere with coating or plating.
[src:casting/anodizing] Ferrous metals are commonly anodized electrolytically in nitric acid or by treatment with red fuming nitric acid to form hard black Iron(II,III) oxide.
[src:casting/anodizing] This oxide remains conformal even when plated on wiring and the wiring is bent.
[src:casting/anodizing] Anodizing changes the microscopic texture of the surface and the crystal structure of the metal near the surface.
[src:casting/anodizing] Thick coatings are normally porous, so a sealing process is often needed to achieve corrosion resistance.
[src:casting/anodizing] Anodized aluminium surfaces, for example, are harder than aluminium but have low to moderate wear resistance that can be improved with increasing thickness or by applying suitable sealing substances.
[src:casting/anodizing] Anodic films are generally much stronger and more adherent than most types of paint and metal plating, but also more brittle.
[src:casting/anodizing] This makes them less likely to crack and peel from ageing and wear, but more susceptible to cracking from thermal stress.
[src:casting/anodizing] Anodizing was first used on an industrial scale in 1923 to protect Duralumin seaplane parts from corrosion.
[src:casting/anodizing] This early chromic acid–based process was called the Bengough–Stuart process and was documented in British defence specification DEF STAN 03-24/3.
[src:casting/anodizing] It is still used today despite its legacy requirements for a complicated voltage cycle now known to be unnecessary.
[src:casting/anodizing] Variations of this process soon evolved, and the first sulfuric acid anodizing process was patented by Gower and O'Brien in 1927.
[src:casting/anodizing] Sulfuric acid soon became and remains the most common anodizing electrolyte.
[src:casting/anodizing] Oxalic acid anodizing was first patented in Japan in 1923 and later widely used in Germany, particularly for architectural applications.
[src:casting/anodizing] Anodized aluminium extrusion was a popular architectural material in the 1960s and 1970s, but has since been displaced by cheaper plastics and powder coating.
[src:casting/anodizing] The phosphoric acid processes are the most recent major development, so far only used as pretreatments for adhesives or organic paints.
[src:casting/anodizing] A wide variety of proprietary and increasingly complex variations of all these anodizing processes continue to be developed by industry, so the growing trend in military and industrial standards is to classify by coating properties rather than by process chemistry.
[src:casting/anodizing] Aluminium alloys are anodized to increase corrosion resistance and to allow dyeing (coloring), improved lubrication, or improved adhesion.
[src:casting/anodizing] However, anodizing does not increase the strength of the aluminium object.
[src:casting/anodizing] When exposed to air at room temperature, or any other gas containing oxygen, pure aluminium self-passivates by forming a surface layer of amorphous aluminium oxide 2 to 3 nm thick, which provides very effective protection against corrosion.
[src:casting/anodizing] Aluminium alloys typically form a thicker oxide layer, 5–15 nm thick, but tend to be more susceptible to corrosion.
[src:casting/anodizing] Aluminium alloy parts are anodized to greatly increase the thickness of this layer for corrosion resistance.
[src:casting/anodizing] The corrosion resistance of aluminium alloys is significantly decreased by certain alloying elements or impurities: copper, iron, and silicon, so 2000-, 4000-, 6000 and 7000-series Al alloys tend to be most susceptible.
[src:casting/anodizing] Although anodizing produces a very regular and uniform coating, microscopic fissures in the coating can lead to corrosion.
[src:casting/anodizing] Further, the coating is susceptible to chemical dissolution in the presence of high- and low-pH chemistry, which results in stripping the coating and corrosion of the substrate.
[src:casting/anodizing] To combat this, various techniques have been developed either to reduce the number of fissures, to insert more chemically stable compounds into the oxide, or both.
[src:casting/anodizing] For instance, sulphuric-anodized articles are normally sealed, either through hydro-thermal sealing or precipitating sealing, to reduce porosity and interstitial pathways that allow corrosive ion exchange between the surface and the substrate.
[src:casting/anodizing] Precipitating seals enhance chemical stability but are less effective in eliminating ionic exchange pathways.
[src:casting/anodizing] Most recently, new techniques to partially convert the amorphous oxide coating into more stable micro-crystalline compounds have been developed that have shown significant improvement based on shorter bond lengths.
[src:casting/anodizing] Some aluminium aircraft parts, architectural materials, and consumer products are anodized.
[src:casting/anodizing] Anodized aluminium can be found on MP3 players, smartphones, multi-tools, flashlights, cookware, cameras, sporting goods, firearms, window frames, roofs, in electrolytic capacitors, and on many other products both for corrosion resistance and the ability to retain dye.
[src:casting/anodizing] Although anodizing only has moderate wear resistance, the deeper pores can better retain a lubricating film than a smooth surface would.
[src:casting/anodizing] Anodized coatings have a much lower thermal conductivity and coefficient of linear expansion than aluminium.
[src:casting/anodizing] As a result, the coating will crack from thermal stress if exposed to temperatures above 80 °C (353 K).
[src:casting/anodizing] The coating can crack, but it will not peel.
[src:casting/anodizing] The melting point of aluminium oxide is 2050 °C (2323K), much higher than pure aluminium's 658 °C (931K).
[src:casting/anodizing] This and the insulativity of aluminium oxide can make welding more difficult.
[src:casting/anodizing] In typical commercial aluminium anodizing processes, the aluminium oxide is grown down into the surface and out from the surface by equal amounts.
[src:casting/anodizing] Therefore, anodizing will increase the part dimensions on each surface by half the oxide thickness.
[src:casting/anodizing] For example, a coating that is 2 μm thick will increase the part dimensions by 1 μm per surface.
[src:casting/anodizing] If the part is anodized on all sides, then all linear dimensions will increase by the oxide thickness.
[src:casting/anodizing] Anodized aluminium surfaces are harder than aluminium but have low to moderate wear resistance, although this can be improved with thickness and sealing.
[src:casting/anodizing] A desmut solution can be applied to the surface of aluminium to remove contaminants.
[src:casting/anodizing] Nitric acid is typically used to remove smut (residue), but is being replaced because of environmental concerns.
[src:casting/anodizing] The anodized aluminium layer is created by passing a direct current through an electrolytic solution, with the aluminium object serving as the anode (the positive electrode in an electrolytic cell).
[src:casting/anodizing] The current releases hydrogen at the cathode (the negative electrode) and oxygen at the surface of the aluminium anode, creating a build-up of aluminium oxide.
[src:casting/anodizing] Alternating current and pulsed current is also possible but rarely used.
[src:casting/anodizing] The voltage required by various solutions may range from 1 to 300 V DC, although most fall in the range of 15 to 21 V.
[src:casting/anodizing] Higher voltages are typically required for thicker coatings formed in sulfuric and organic acid.
[src:casting/anodizing] The anodizing current varies with the area of aluminium being anodized and typically ranges from 30 to 300 A/m2.
[src:casting/anodizing] Aluminium anodizing (eloxal or **El**ectrolytic **Ox**idation of **Al**uminium) is usually performed in an acidic solution, typically sulphuric acid or chromic acid, which slowly dissolves the aluminium oxide.
[src:casting/anodizing] The acid action is balanced with the oxidation rate to form a coating with nanopores, 10–150 nm in diameter.
[src:casting/anodizing] These pores are what allow the electrolyte solution and current to reach the aluminium substrate and continue growing the coating to greater thickness beyond what is produced by auto-passivation.
[src:casting/anodizing] These pores allow for the dye to be absorbed, however, this must be followed by sealing or the dye will not stay.
[src:casting/anodizing] Dye is typically followed up by a clean nickel acetate seal.
[src:casting/anodizing] Because the dye is only superficial, the underlying oxide may continue to provide corrosion protection even if minor wear and scratches break through the dyed layer.
[src:casting/anodizing] Conditions such as electrolyte concentration, acidity, solution temperature, and current must be controlled to allow the formation of a consistent oxide layer.
[src:casting/anodizing] Harder, thicker films tend to be produced by more concentrated solutions at lower temperatures with higher voltages and currents.
[src:casting/anodizing] The film thickness can range from under 0.5 micrometers for bright decorative work up to 150 micrometers for architectural applications.
[src:casting/anodizing] Anodizing can be performed in combination with chromate conversion coating.
[src:casting/anodizing] Each process provides corrosion resistance, with anodizing offering a significant advantage when it comes to ruggedness or physical wear resistance.
[src:casting/anodizing] The reason for combining the processes can vary, however, the significant difference between anodizing and chromate conversion coating is the electrical conductivity of the films produced.
[src:casting/anodizing] Although both stable compounds, chromate conversion coating has a greatly increased electrical conductivity.
[src:casting/anodizing] Applications where this may be useful are varied, however the issue of grounding components as part of a larger system is an obvious one.
[src:casting/anodizing] The dual finishing process uses the best each process has to offer, anodizing with its hard wear resistance and chromate conversion coating with its electrical conductivity.
[src:casting/anodizing] The process steps can typically involve chromate conversion coating the entire component, followed by a masking of the surface in areas where the chromate coating must remain intact.
[src:casting/anodizing] Beyond that, the chromate coating is then dissolved in unmasked areas.
[src:casting/anodizing] The component can then be anodized, with anodizing taking to the unmasked areas.
[src:casting/anodizing] The exact process will vary dependent on service provider, component geometry and required outcome.
[src:casting/anodizing] The most widely used anodizing specification in the US is a U.S. military spec, MIL-A-8625, which defines three types of aluminium anodizing.
[src:casting/anodizing] Type I is chromic acid anodizing, Type II is sulphuric acid anodizing, and Type III is sulphuric acid hard anodizing.
[src:casting/anodizing] None of these specifications define a detailed process or chemistry, but rather a set of tests and quality assurance measures which the anodized product must meet.
[src:casting/anodizing] BS 1615 guides the selection of alloys for anodizing.
[src:casting/anodizing] For British defense work, a detailed chromic and sulfuric anodizing processes are described by DEF STAN 03-24/3 and DEF STAN 03-25/3 respectively.
[src:casting/anodizing] The oldest anodizing process uses chromic acid.
[src:casting/anodizing] It is widely known as the Bengough-Stuart process but, due to the safety regulations regarding air quality control, is not preferred by vendors when the additive material associated with type II doesn't break tolerances.
[src:casting/anodizing] In North America, it is known as Type I because it is so designated by the MIL-A-8625 standard, but it is also covered by AMS 2470 and MIL-A-8625 Type IB.
[src:casting/anodizing] In the UK it is normally specified as Def Stan 03/24 and used in areas that are prone to come into contact with propellants etc.
[src:casting/anodizing] There are also Boeing and Airbus standards.
[src:casting/anodizing] Chromic acid produces thinner, 0.5 μm to 18 μm (0.00002" to 0.0007") more opaque films that are softer, ductile, and to a degree self-healing.
[src:casting/anodizing] They are harder to dye and may be applied as a pretreatment before painting.
[src:casting/anodizing] The method of film formation is different from using sulfuric acid in that the voltage is ramped up through the process cycle.
[src:casting/anodizing] Sulfuric acid is the most widely used solution to produce an anodized coating.
[src:casting/anodizing] Coatings of moderate thickness 1.8 μm to 25 μm (0.00007" to 0.001") are known as Type II in North America, as named by MIL-A-8625, while coatings thicker than 25 μm (0.001") are known as Type III, hard-coat, hard anodizing, or engineered anodizing.
[src:casting/anodizing] Very thin coatings similar to those produced by chromic anodizing are known as Type IIB.
[src:casting/anodizing] Thick coatings require more process control, and are produced in a refrigerated tank near the freezing point of water with higher voltages than the thinner coatings.
[src:casting/anodizing] Hard anodizing can be made between 13 and 150 μm (0.0005" to 0.006") thick.
[src:casting/anodizing] Anodizing thickness increases wear resistance, corrosion resistance, ability to retain lubricants and PTFE coatings, and electrical and thermal insulation.
[src:casting/anodizing] Sealing Type III will improve corrosion resistance at the cost of reducing abrasion resistance.
[src:casting/anodizing] Standards for thin (Soft/Standard) sulfuric anodizing are given by MIL-A-8625 Types II and IIB, AMS 2471 (undyed), and AMS 2472 (dyed), BS EN ISO 12373/1 (decorative), BS 3987 (Architectural).
[src:casting/anodizing] Standards for thick sulphuric anodizing are given by MIL-A-8625 Type III, AMS 2469, BS ISO 10074, BS EN 2536 and the obsolete AMS 2468 and DEF STAN 03-26/1.
[src:casting/anodizing] Anodizing can produce yellowish integral colors without dyes if it is carried out in weak acids with high voltages, high current densities, and strong refrigeration.
[src:casting/anodizing] Shades of color are restricted to a range which includes pale yellow, gold, deep bronze, brown, grey, and black.
[src:casting/anodizing] Some advanced variations can produce a white coating with 80% reflectivity.
[src:casting/anodizing] The shade of color produced is sensitive to variations in the metallurgy of the underlying alloy and cannot be reproduced consistently.
[src:casting/anodizing] Anodizing in some organic acids, for example malic acid, can enter a 'runaway' situation, in which the current drives the acid to attack the aluminium far more aggressively than normal, resulting in huge pits and scarring.
[src:casting/anodizing] Also, if the current or voltage are driven too high, 'burning' can set in; in this case, the supplies act as if nearly shorted and large, uneven and amorphous black regions develop.
[src:casting/anodizing] Integral color anodizing is generally done with organic acids, but the same effect has been produced in laboratories with very dilute sulfuric acid.
[src:casting/anodizing] Integral color anodizing was originally performed with oxalic acid, but sulfonated aromatic compounds containing oxygen, particularly sulfosalicylic acid, have been more common since the 1960s.
[src:casting/anodizing] Thicknesses of up to 50 μm can be achieved.
[src:casting/anodizing] Organic acid anodizing is called Type IC by MIL-A-8625.
[src:casting/anodizing] Anodizing can be carried out in phosphoric acid, usually as a surface preparation for adhesives.
[src:casting/anodizing] This is described in standard ASTM D3933.
[src:casting/anodizing] Anodizing can also be performed in borate or tartrate baths in which aluminium oxide is insoluble.
[src:casting/anodizing] In these processes, the coating growth stops when the part is fully covered, and the thickness is linearly related to the voltage applied.
[src:casting/anodizing] These coatings are free of pores, relative to the sulfuric and chromic acid processes.
[src:casting/anodizing] This type of coating is widely used to make electrolytic capacitors because the thin aluminium films (typically less than 0.5 μm) would risk being pierced by acidic processes.
[src:casting/anodizing] Plasma electrolytic oxidation is a similar process, but where higher voltages are applied.
[src:casting/anodizing] This causes sparks to occur and results in more crystalline/ceramic type coatings.
[src:casting/anodizing] Magnesium is anodized primarily as a primer for paint.
[src:casting/anodizing] A thin (5 μm) film is sufficient for this.
[src:casting/anodizing] Thicker coatings of 25 μm and up can provide mild corrosion resistance when sealed with oil, wax, or sodium silicate.
[src:casting/anodizing] Standards for magnesium anodizing are given in AMS 2466, AMS 2478, AMS 2479, and ASTM B893.
[src:casting/anodizing] Niobium anodizes in a similar fashion to titanium with a range of attractive colors being formed by interference at different film thicknesses.
[src:casting/anodizing] Again the film thickness is dependent on the anodizing voltage.
[src:casting/anodizing] Uses include jewelry and commemorative coins.
[src:casting/anodizing] Stainless steel can be anodized in baths containing sulphuric acid and hexavalent chromium compounds.
[src:casting/anodizing] Tantalum anodizes similarly to titanium and niobium with a range of attractive colors being formed by interference at different film thicknesses.
[src:casting/anodizing] Again the film thickness is dependent on the anodizing voltage and typically ranges from 18 to 23 Angstroms per volt depending on electrolyte and temperature.
[src:casting/anodizing] An anodized oxide layer has a thickness in the range of 30 nanometers (1.2×10−6 in) to several micrometers.
[src:casting/anodizing] Standards for titanium anodizing are given by AMS 2487 and AMS 2488.
[src:casting/anodizing] AMS 2488 Type III anodizing of titanium generates an array of different colors without dyes, for which it is sometimes used in art, costume jewellery, body piercing jewellery and wedding rings.
[src:casting/anodizing] The color formed is dependent on the thickness of the oxide (which is determined by the anodizing voltage); it is caused by the interference of light reflecting off the oxide surface with light travelling through it and reflecting off the underlying metal surface.
[src:casting/anodizing] AMS 2488 Type II anodizing produces a thicker matte grey finish with higher wear resistance.
[src:casting/anodizing] Zinc is rarely anodized, but a process was developed by the International Lead Zinc Research Organization and covered by MIL-A-81801.
[src:casting/anodizing] A solution of ammonium phosphate, chromate and fluoride with voltages of up to 200 V can produce olive green coatings up to 80 μm thick.
[src:casting/anodizing] The coatings are hard and corrosion resistant.
[src:casting/anodizing] Zinc or galvanized steel can be anodized using DC at lower voltages (20–30 V) in silicate baths containing varying concentrations of sodium silicate, sodium hydroxide, borax, sodium nitrite, and nickel sulfate.
[src:casting/anodizing] The most common anodizing processes, for example, sulphuric acid on aluminium, produce a porous surface which can accept dyes easily.
[src:casting/anodizing] The number of dye colors is almost endless; however, the colors produced tend to vary according to the base alloy.
[src:casting/anodizing] The most common colors in the industry, due to them being relatively cheap, are yellow, green, blue, black, orange, purple and red.
[src:casting/anodizing] Though some may prefer lighter colors, in practice, they may be difficult to produce on certain alloys such as high-silicon casting grades and 2000-series aluminium-copper alloys.
[src:casting/anodizing] Another concern is the "lightfastness" of organic dyestuffs—some colors (reds and blues) are particularly prone to fading.
[src:casting/anodizing] Black dyes and gold produced by inorganic means (ferric ammonium oxalate) are more lightfast.
[src:casting/anodizing] Dyed anodizing is usually sealed to reduce or eliminate dye bleedout.
[src:casting/anodizing] White color cannot be applied due to the larger molecule size than the pore size of the oxide layer.
[src:casting/anodizing] Another interesting coloring method is anodizing interference coloring.
[src:casting/anodizing] The thin oil film resting on the water's surface displays a rainbow hue due to the interference between light reflected from the water-oil interface and the oil film's surface.
[src:casting/anodizing] Because the oil film's thickness isn't regulated, the resulting rainbow color appears random.
[src:casting/anodizing] In the anodizing coloring of aluminum, desired colors are achieved by depositing a controllably thick metal layer (typically tin) at the base of the porous structure.
[src:casting/anodizing] This involves reflections on the aluminum substrate and the upper metal surface.
[src:casting/anodizing] The color resulting from interference shifts from blue, green, and yellow to red as the deposited metal layer thickens.
[src:casting/anodizing] Beyond a specific thickness, the optical interference vanishes, and the color turns bronze.
[src:casting/anodizing] Interference-colored anodized aluminum parts exhibit a distinctive quality: their color varies when viewed from different angles.
[src:casting/anodizing] The interference coloring involves a 3-step process: sulfuric acid anodizing, electrochemical modification of the anodic pore, and metal (tin) deposition.
[src:casting/anodizing] Sealing is the final step in the anodizing process.
[src:casting/anodizing] Acidic anodizing solutions produce pores in the anodized coating.
[src:casting/anodizing] These pores can absorb dyes and retain lubricants, but are also an avenue for corrosion.
[src:casting/anodizing] When lubrication properties are not critical, they are usually sealed after dyeing to increase corrosion resistance and dye retention.
[src:casting/anodizing] There are three most common types of sealing.
[src:casting/anodizing] Mid-temperature sealing process which works at 160–180 °F (70–80 °C) in solutions containing organic additives and metal salts.
[src:casting/anodizing] However, this process will likely leach the colors.
[src:casting/anodizing] Cold sealing process, where the pores are closed by impregnation of a sealant in a room-temperature bath, is more popular due to energy savings.
[src:casting/anodizing] Coatings sealed in this method are not suitable for adhesive bonding.
[src:casting/anodizing] Teflon, nickel acetate, cobalt acetate, and hot sodium or potassium dichromate seals are commonly used.
[src:casting/anodizing] MIL-A-8625 requires sealing for thin coatings (Types I and II) and allows it as an option for thick ones (Type III).
[src:casting/anodizing] Anodized aluminium surfaces that are not regularly cleaned are susceptible to panel edge staining, a unique type of surface staining that can affect the structural integrity of the metal.
[src:casting/anodizing] Anodizing is one of the more environmentally friendly metal finishing processes.
[src:casting/anodizing] Except for organic (aka integral color) anodizing, the by-products contain only small amounts of heavy metals, halogens, or volatile organic compounds.
[src:casting/anodizing] Integral color anodizing produces no VOCs, heavy metals, or halogens as all of the byproducts found in the effluent streams of other processes come from their dyes or plating materials.
[src:casting/anodizing] The most common anodizing effluents, aluminium hydroxide and aluminium sulfate, are recycled for the manufacturing of alum, baking powder, cosmetics, newsprint and fertilizer or used by industrial wastewater treatment systems.
[src:casting/anodizing] Anodizing will raise the surface since the oxide created occupies more space than the base metal converted.
[src:casting/anodizing] This will generally not be of consequence except where there are tight tolerances.
[src:casting/anodizing] If so, the thickness of the anodizing layer has to be taken into account when choosing the machining dimension.
[src:casting/anodizing] A general practice on engineering drawing is to specify that "dimensions apply after all surface finishes".
[src:casting/anodizing] This will force the machine shop to take into account the anodization thickness when performing the final machining of the mechanical part before anodization.
[src:casting/anodizing] Also, in the case of small holes threaded to accept screws, anodizing may cause the screws to bind, thus, the threaded holes may need to be chased with a tap to restore the original dimensions.
[src:casting/anodizing] Alternatively, special oversize taps may be used to precompensate for this growth.
[src:casting/anodizing] In the case of unthreaded holes that accept fixed-diameter pins or rods, a slightly oversized hole to allow for the dimension change may be appropriate.
[src:casting/anodizing] Depending on the alloy and thickness of the anodized coating, the same may have a significantly negative effect on fatigue life.
[src:casting/anodizing] Conversely, anodizing may increase fatigue life by preventing corrosion pitting.
[src:casting/anvil] An **anvil** is a metalworking tool consisting of a large block of metal (usually forged or cast steel), with a flattened top surface, upon which another object is struck (or "worked").
[src:casting/anvil] Anvils are massive because having higher inertia allows them to more efficiently cause the energy of striking tools to be transferred to the work piece.
[src:casting/anvil] In most cases an anvil is used as a forging tool.
[src:casting/anvil] Before the advent of modern welding technology, it was the primary tool of metal workers.
[src:casting/anvil] A great majority of modern anvils are made of cast steel that has been heat-treated by either flame or electric induction.
[src:casting/anvil] Inexpensive anvils have been made of cast iron and low-quality steel, but are considered unsuitable for serious use, as they deform and lack rebound when struck.
[src:casting/anvil] The primary work surface of the anvil is known as the face.
[src:casting/anvil] It is generally made of hardened steel and should be flat and smooth with rounded edges for most work.
[src:casting/anvil] Any marks on the face will be transferred to the work.
[src:casting/anvil] Also, sharp edges tend to cut into the metal being worked and may cause cracks to form in the workpiece.
[src:casting/anvil] The face is hardened and tempered to resist the blows of the smith's hammer, so the anvil face does not deform under repeated use.
[src:casting/anvil] A hard anvil face also reduces the amount of force lost in each hammer blow.
[src:casting/anvil] Hammers, tools, and work pieces of hardened steel should never directly strike the anvil face with full force, as they may damage it; this can result in chipping or deforming of the anvil face.
[src:casting/anvil] The horn of the anvil is a conical projection used to form various round shapes and is generally unhardened steel or iron.
[src:casting/anvil] The horn is used mostly in bending operations.
[src:casting/anvil] It also is used by some smiths as an aid in "drawing down" stock (making it longer and thinner).
[src:casting/anvil] Some anvils, mainly European, are made with two horns, one square and one round.
[src:casting/anvil] Also, some anvils are made with side horns or clips for specialized work.
[src:casting/anvil] The *step* is the area of the anvil between the "horn" and the "face".
[src:casting/anvil] It is soft and is used for cutting; its purpose is to prevent damaging the steel face of the anvil by conducting such operations there and so as not to damage the cutting edge of the chisel, though many smiths shun this practice as it will damage the anvil over time.
[src:casting/anvil] There have also been other additions to the anvil such as an upsetting block; this is used to upset steel, generally in long strips/bars as it is placed between the feet of the anvil.
[src:casting/anvil] Upsetting is a technique often used by blacksmiths for making the steel workpiece short and thick, having probably been originally long and thin.
[src:casting/anvil] The *hardy hole* is a square hole into which specialized forming and cutting tools, called hardy tools, are placed.
[src:casting/anvil] It is also used in punching and bending operations.
[src:casting/anvil] These are not to be confused with swage blocks, although their purpose is similar.
[src:casting/anvil] The *pritchel hole* is a small round hole that is present on most modern anvils.
[src:casting/anvil] At times, smiths will fit a second tool to this hole to allow the smith more flexibility when using more than one anvil tool.
[src:casting/anvil] The anvil is placed as near to the forge as is convenient, generally no more than one step from the forge to prevent heat loss in the work piece.
[src:casting/anvil] An anvil needs to be placed upon a sturdy base made from an impact and fire resistant material.
[src:casting/anvil] Common methods of attaching an anvil are spikes, chains, steel or iron straps, clips, bolts where there are holes provided, and cables.
[src:casting/anvil] The most common base traditionally was a hard wood log or large timber buried several feet into the floor of the forge shop.
[src:casting/anvil] In the industrial era, cast-iron bases became available.
[src:casting/anvil] They had the advantage of adding additional weight to the anvil, making it more stable.
[src:casting/anvil] These bases are highly sought after by collectors today.
[src:casting/anvil] When concrete became widely available, there was a trend to make steel-reinforced anvil bases by some smiths, though this practice has largely been abandoned.
[src:casting/anvil] In more modern times, anvils have been placed upon bases fabricated from steel, often a short thick section of a large I-beam.
[src:casting/anvil] In addition, bases have been made from dimensional lumber bolted together to form a large block or steel drums full of oil-saturated sand to provide a damping effect.
[src:casting/anvil] In recent times, tripod bases of fabricated steel have become popular.
[src:casting/anvil] There are many designs for anvils, which are often tailored for a specific purpose or to meet the needs of a particular smith.
[src:casting/anvil] For example, there were anvils specifically made for farriers, general smiths, cutlers, chain makers, armorers, saw tuners, coach makers, coopers, and many other types of metal workers.
[src:casting/anvil] Most of these anvil types look similar, but some are radically different.
[src:casting/anvil] Saw maker anvils, for instance, are generally large rectangular blocks of steel that have a harder surface than most other anvils due to hammering on a harder steel for saws.
[src:casting/anvil] Bladesmith anvils tend to be rectangular with a hardy and pritchel, but no horn.
[src:casting/anvil] Such designs have originated in diverse geographic locations.
[src:casting/anvil] Several styles of anvils include Bavarian, French Pig anvil, Austrian, and Chinese turtle anvil.
[src:casting/anvil] The Bavarian style is known for the sloped brow.
[src:casting/anvil] The brow was first used in medieval times to make armor on the church windows below the brow.
[src:casting/anvil] Common manufactures include Söding Halbach and Holthaus.
[src:casting/anvil] This style of anvil is known not to sway in the face due to the extra mass with the brow.
[src:casting/anvil] The common blacksmith's anvil is made of either forged or cast steel, forged wrought iron with a hard steel face or cast iron with a hard steel face.
[src:casting/anvil] Cast-iron anvils are not used for forging as they are incapable of standing up to the impact and will crack and dent.
[src:casting/anvil] Also, cast-iron anvils without a hard steel face do not have the rebound that a harder anvil would and will tire out the smith.
[src:casting/anvil] Historically, some anvils have been made with a smooth top working face of hardened steel welded to a cast-iron or wrought-iron body, though this manufacturing method is no longer in use.
[src:casting/anvil] At one end, the common smith's anvil has a projecting conical *bick* (*beak*, *horn*) used for hammering curved work pieces.
[src:casting/anvil] The other end is typically called the heel.
[src:casting/anvil] Occasionally, the other end is also provided with a bick, partly rectangular in section.
[src:casting/anvil] Most anvils made since the late 18th century also have a hardy hole and a pritchel hole where various tools, such as the anvil-cutter or hot chisel, can be inserted and held by the anvil.
[src:casting/anvil] Some anvils have several hardy and pritchel holes, to accommodate a wider variety of hardy tools and pritchels.
[src:casting/anvil] An anvil may also have a softer *pad* for chisel work.
[src:casting/anvil] An anvil for a power hammer is usually supported on a massive anvil block, sometimes weighing over 800 tons for a 12-ton hammer; this again rests on a strong foundation of timber and masonry or concrete.
[src:casting/anvil] An anvil may have a marking indicating its weight, manufacturer, or place of origin.
[src:casting/anvil] American-made anvils were often marked in pounds.
[src:casting/anvil] European anvils are sometimes marked in kilograms.
[src:casting/anvil] English anvils were often marked in hundredweight, the marking consisting of three numbers, indicating hundredweight, quarter hundredweight and pounds.
[src:casting/anvil] Cheap anvils made from inferior steel or cast iron and often sold at retail hardware stores, are considered unsuitable for serious use, and are often derisively referred to as "ASOs", or "anvil shaped objects".
[src:casting/anvil] In recent years, inexpensive cast steel anvils with hardened faces have become common, often sold online.
[src:casting/anvil] Some blacksmiths consider these anvils suitable for beginners.
[src:casting/anvil] Amateur smiths have used lengths of railroad rail, forklift tines, or even simple blocks of steel as makeshift anvils.
[src:casting/anvil] A metalworking vise may have a small anvil integrated into its design.
[src:casting/anvil] Anvils were first made of stone, then bronze, and later wrought iron.
[src:casting/anvil] As steel became more readily available, anvils were faced with it.
[src:casting/anvil] This was done to give the anvil a hard face and to stop the anvil from deforming from impact.
[src:casting/anvil] Many regional styles of anvils evolved through time from the simple block that was first used by smiths.
[src:casting/anvil] The majority of anvils found today in the US are based on the London pattern anvil of the mid-19th century.
[src:casting/anvil] The wrought-iron steel-faced anvil was produced up until the early 20th century.
[src:casting/anvil] Through the 19th and very early 20th centuries, this method of construction evolved to produce extremely high-quality anvils.
[src:casting/anvil] The basic process involved forge-welding billets of wrought iron together to produce the desired shape.
[src:casting/anvil] The sequence and location of the forge-welds varied between different anvil makers and the kind of anvil being made.
[src:casting/anvil] At the same time cast-iron anvils with steel faces were being made in the United States.
[src:casting/anvil] At the dawn of the 20th century solid cast-steel anvils began to be produced, as well as two-piece forged anvils made from closed-die forgings.
[src:casting/anvil] Modern anvils are generally made entirely from steel.
[src:casting/anvil] There are many references to anvils in ancient Greek and Egyptian writings, including Homer's works.
[src:casting/anvil] They have been found at the Calico Early Man Site in North America.
[src:casting/anvil] Anvils have since lost their former commonness, along with the smiths who used them.
[src:casting/anvil] Mechanized production has made cheap and abundant manufactured goods readily available.
[src:casting/anvil] The one-off handmade products of the blacksmith are less economically viable in the modern world, while in the past they were an absolute necessity.
[src:casting/anvil] However, anvils are still used by blacksmiths and metal workers of all kinds in producing custom work.
[src:casting/anvil] They are also essential to the work done by farriers.
[src:casting/anvil] Anvil firing is the practice of firing an anvil into the air using gunpowder.
[src:casting/anvil] It has been popular in California, the eastern United States and the southern United States, much like how fireworks are used today.
[src:casting/anvil] There is a growing interest in re-enacting this "ancient tradition" in the US, which has now spread to England.
[src:casting/anvil] A typical metalworker's anvil, with horn at one end and flat face at the other, is a standard prop for cartoon gags, as the epitome of a heavy and clumsy object that is perfect for dropping onto people.
[src:casting/anvil] This visual metaphor is common, for example, in Warner Brothers' *Looney Tunes* and *Merrie Melodies* shorts, such as those with Wile E.
[src:casting/anvil] An episode of *Gilmore Girls* referred to anvils in cartoons when one of the main characters tries to have a conversation about "Where did all the anvils go?", a reference to their falling out of use on a general scale.
[src:casting/anvil] *Animaniacs* made frequent gags on the topic throughout its run, even having a kingdom named Anvilania, whose sole national product is anvils.
[src:casting/anvil] Dwarves were blacksmiths who used anvils for metalworking in C.
[src:casting/anvil] Lewis's *The Chronicles of Narnia*, most iconically on *The Magician's Nephew* and *Prince Caspian*; as well as in J.
[src:casting/anvil] Wagner's *Ring des Nibelungen* is notable in using the anvil as pitched percussion.
[src:casting/anvil] The vast majority of extant works use the anvil as unpitched.
[src:casting/anvil] However **tuned anvils** are available as musical instruments, albeit unusual.
[src:casting/anvil] These are not to be confused with the "sawyers' anvils" used to "tune" big circular saw blades.
[src:casting/anvil] Steel anvils are used for tuning for use as musical instruments, because those based partly on cast iron and similar materials give a duller sound; this is actually valued in industry, as pure steel anvils are troublesomely noisy, though energetically more efficient.
[src:casting/anvil] The hammer and anvil have enjoyed varying popularity in orchestral roles.
[src:casting/anvil] Robert Donington pointed out that Sebastian Virdung notes them in his book of 1510, and Martin Agricola includes it in his list of instruments (Musica instrumentalis deudsch, 1529) largely as a compliment to Pythagoras.
[src:casting/anvil] In pre-modern or modern times anvils occasionally appear in operatic works by Berlioz, Bizet, Gounod, Verdi, and Wagner for example.
[src:casting/anvil] Commonly pairs of anvils tuned a third apart are used.
[src:casting/anvil] In practice modern orchestras commonly substitute a brake drum or other suitable steel structure that is easier to tune than an actual anvil, although a visibly convincing anvil-shaped prop may be shown as desired.
[src:casting/anvil] In *Das Rheingold* Wagner scored for nine little, six mid-sized, and three large anvils, but orchestras seldom can afford instrumentation on such a scale.
[src:casting/anyang] Anyang is the location of the ancient city of Yin, which was the capital of the Shang dynasty and the first stable capital of China.
[src:casting/anyang] As the ancient capital of the Seven Dynasties and one of the birthplaces of Chinese civilization, Anyang is rich in historical and cultural resources and has a number of world-class and national historical sites.
[src:casting/anyang] At the end of 1986, it was recognized as a national historical and cultural city.
[src:casting/anyang] Xiaonanhai, on the far western edge of the city, was home to prehistoric cavemen during the Stone Age.
[src:casting/anyang] Over 7,000 artifacts (including stone tools and animal bone fossils) have been unearthed here, representing what has been dubbed the Xiaonanhai culture.
[src:casting/anyang] Around 2000 BC, the legendary sage-kings Zhuanxu and Emperor Ku are said to have established their capitals in the area around modern Anyang from where they ruled their kingdoms.
[src:casting/anyang] Today their mausoleums are situated in Sanyang village south of Neihuang County.
[src:casting/anyang] At the beginning of the 14th century BC, King Pangeng of the Shang dynasty established his capital 2 km (1.2 mi) north of the modern city on the banks of the Huan River.
[src:casting/anyang] The city, known as **Yin**, was the first stable capital in Chinese history and from that point on the dynasty that founded it would also become known as the Yin dynasty.
[src:casting/anyang] The capital served 12 kings in 8 generations including Wu Ding, under whom the dynasty reached the zenith of its power, until it was wiped out along with the dynasty that was founded by King Wu of the Zhou in 1046 BC.
[src:casting/anyang] Anyang was made the county seat of Anyang County c.
[src:casting/anyang] 607 CE and it has held that position ever since.
[src:casting/anyang] Anyang's Tangyin County was the ancient seat of Yue Village, the birthplace of the famous Song dynasty general, Yue Fei.
[src:casting/anyang] This was also the historic home of Zhou Tong, Yue's military arts tutor (though fictional sources place him in Shaanxi).
[src:casting/anyang] The town was known as **Zhangde** (彰德) until 1912, when it was given its present name of Anyang, following the establishment of the Republic of China.
[src:casting/anyang] In August 1949, Anyang prefecture was detached from Henan and – along with Puyang and Xinxiang – consigned to the short lived experimental province of Pingyuan by the ruling Communist government.
[src:casting/anyang] All three were eventually returned to Henan's territory in November 1953, with the dissolution of Pingyuan.
[src:casting/anyang] Anyang spans a total area of 7,355 square kilometres (2,840 sq mi).
[src:casting/anyang] The city's elevation is generally higher in the west, with the foothills of the Taihang Mountains running through the area, and lower in the east, which comprises part of the North China Plain.
[src:casting/anyang] Anyang has a four-season, monsoon-influenced humid continental climate/semi-arid climate (Köppen *Dwa/BSk*).
[src:casting/anyang] Winters are cold and very dry, with a January 24-hour average of −0.8 °C (30.6 °F).
[src:casting/anyang] Summers are hot and humid, with July averaging 27.2 °C (81.0 °F).
[src:casting/anyang] A majority of the annual precipitation of 552 mm (21.7 in) falls in July and August alone, and the annual mean temperature is 14.28 °C (57.7 °F).
[src:casting/anyang] With monthly percent possible sunshine ranging from 43% in July to 58% in May, the city receives 2,225 hours of bright sunshine annually, with April to June the sunniest period.
[src:casting/anyang] There are more northerly winds in winter, while southerly winds dominate in summer.
[src:casting/anyang] The prefecture-level city of Anyang administers 9 county-level administrative divisions, including 4 districts, 1 county-level city, and 4 counties.
[src:casting/anyang] These, in turn, administer 46 subdistricts, 66 towns, and 23 townships, which then administer 302 residential communities and 2,979 administrative villages.
[src:casting/anyang] Per the 2020 Chinese Census, Anyang has a population of 5.48 million people.
[src:casting/anyang] The overwhelming majority of the city's population is ethnically Han Chinese, with ethnic minorities constituting a population of around 10,000 people.
[src:casting/anyang] 43 different ethnic minorities live in the city, with prominent ethnic minority communities including the Hui, Mongols, Manchus, Zhuang, Miao, Tibetans, and the Yi.
[src:casting/anyang] Anyang is a largely industrial city, with major industries including the production of metals such as iron and steel, coal coking, and clothing production.
[src:casting/anyang] Major Chinese steel producer Shagang Group has operations in Anyang.
[src:casting/anyang] Major mineral reserves in Anyang include dolomite, potassium-bearing shale, nepheline syenite, quartzite, limestone, and clay.
[src:casting/anyang] The city's total gross domestic product (GDP) totaled 243.55 billion renminbi (RMB) as of 2021, a 5% increase from the prior year.
[src:casting/anyang] Anyang's primary sector comprised 9.7% of the city's GDP, the secondary sector comprised 43.7%, and the tertiary sector comprised 46.6%.
[src:casting/anyang] The per capita disposable income in Anyang totaled 27,365 RMB as of 2021, an increase of 7.2% from 2020.
[src:casting/anyang] The per capita disposable income of Anyang's urban residents was 37,464 RMB, a 6% annual increase, and the per capita disposable income of rural residents was 18,424 RMB, an 8.4% annual increase.
[src:casting/anyang] Sixteen foreign-funded enterprises (joint ventures, cooperative enterprises, and wholly foreign-owned enterprises) have been established in Anyang.
[src:casting/anyang] Recently, Anyang has established an economic and technological development zone covering a total area of 22.8 km2 (8.8 sq mi), and issued a series of preferential policies to attract many domestic Chinese and foreign businesses.
[src:casting/anyang] The Anyang Hongqiqu Airport opened on November 29, 2023.
[src:casting/anyang] Anyang Hongqiqu Airport is located in the junction area of Anyang, Puyang and Hebi cities, covering an area of approximately 2,339 acres.
[src:casting/anyang] The total project investment is 1.366 billion yuan.
[src:casting/anyang] It is positioned as a domestic civil regional airport with a flight area level of 4C.
[src:casting/anyang] The opening of the airport will directly serve the air travel of 11.6 million people in the three cities in northern Henan, and radiate about 60 million people within 150 kilometers of eastern Shanxi, southern Hebei and southwestern Shandong.
[src:casting/anyang] Anyang city is an ancient city with a history of over 3,000 years and is one of the Eight Ancient Capitals of China, and also one of the best preserved.
[src:casting/anyang] It is one of the key birthplaces of Chinese ancient culture.
[src:casting/anyang] At the same time, it is a national historical and cultural city, the hometown of Oracle, the birthplace of the Book of Changes, the birthplace of the spirit of the Red Flag Canal, and the location of the world cultural heritage Yin Ruins, Cao Cao's Gaoling, and the Museum of Chinese Characters.
[src:casting/anyang] The city has three large museums: the Anyang Museum, the National Museum of Chinese Writing, and the Yinxu Museum on the ruins and royal tombs of the Shang dynasty.
[src:casting/anyang] Anyang also has beautiful natural scenery—the Taihang Linlu Hill Scenic Area on the 400-km Taihang Mountains and the grand 1,500-km Red Flag Canal.
[src:casting/anyang] Changchun Temple, a Taoist shrine, was built on the hillside of the mountains surrounding it during the Tang dynasty.
[src:casting/anyang] It was officially opened to the public on 1 May 2014, after a period of cautious restoration.
[src:casting/anyang] Tianning Si (Mansion Temple) was established during the Tang dynasty, and has recently been restored by the Protection and Research Institute of Ancient Architecture of Anyang City, and opened to the public.
[src:casting/anyang] Wenfeng Ta (Literature Peak Pagoda) on the grounds of the Tianning Temple is believed to have been constructed in 925 and is known, from inscriptions concerning the reconstruction of the temple, to have been in place by 952.
[src:casting/anyang] The current pagoda was constructed during the Ming dynasty and received its current name during the Qing dynasty due to its proximity to the Confucian temple.
[src:casting/anyang] The five-story dark red brick octagonal tower is 38.65m high and is, unusually, larger at the top than the bottom and is topped with a 10-metre Lamaist stupa-style dagoba steeple.
[src:casting/anyang] The pagoda stands on a two-metre-high stone pedestal and is decorated with multi-eave pent roofs and carvings of Buddhas and bodhisattvas.
[src:casting/anyang] The unique pagoda is the symbol of Anyang.
[src:casting/anyang] Located about 2 km (1.2 mi) northwest of Anyang are the ruins of the Shang dynasty capital known as Yin.
[src:casting/anyang] This massive archaeological site was discovered in 1899, excavated in the decades that followed, and first opened to the public in the 1980s as the Garden Museum of Yinxu.
[src:casting/anyang] The current Yinxu museum was opened on 16 March 2005, and includes the famous Tomb of Fu Hao.
[src:casting/anyang] The site was later designated a UNESCO World Heritage Sites in 2006.
[src:casting/bandsaw] A **bandsaw** (also written **band saw**) is a power saw with a long, sharp blade with two ends welded together to form an oval band.
[src:casting/bandsaw] The banded blade of toothed metal is stretched between two or more wheels to cut material.
[src:casting/bandsaw] They are used principally in woodworking, metalworking, and lumber milling, but may cut a variety of materials.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Advantages include uniform cutting action as a result of an evenly distributed tooth load, and the ability to cut irregular or curved shapes like a jigsaw.
[src:casting/bandsaw] The minimum radius of a curve is determined by the width of the band and its kerf.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Most bandsaws have two wheels rotating in the same plane, one of which is powered, although some may have three or four to distribute the load.
[src:casting/bandsaw] The blade itself can come in a variety of sizes and tooth pitches (teeth per inch, or TPI), which enables the machine to be highly versatile and able to cut a wide variety of materials including wood, metal and plastic.
[src:casting/bandsaw] A band saw is recommended for use in cutting metal as it produces much less toxic fumes and particulates when compared with an angle grinder or reciprocating saw.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Almost all bandsaws today are powered by an electric motor.
[src:casting/bandsaw] The idea of the bandsaw dates back to at least 1809, when William Newberry received a British patent for the idea, but bandsaws remained impractical largely because of the inability to produce accurate and durable blades using the technology of the day.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Constant flexing of the blade over the wheels caused either the material or the joint welding it into a loop to fail.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Nearly 40 years passed before Frenchwoman Anne Paulin Crepin devised a welding technique overcoming this hurdle.
[src:casting/bandsaw] She applied for a patent in 1846, and soon afterward sold the right to employ it to manufacturer A.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Combining this method with new steel alloys and advanced tempering techniques allowed Perin to create the first modern bandsaw blade.
[src:casting/bandsaw] The first American bandsaw patent was granted to Benjamin Barker of Ellsworth, Maine, in January 1836.
[src:casting/bandsaw] The first factory produced and commercially available bandsaw in the U.S. was by a design of Paul Prybil.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Power hacksaws (with reciprocating blades) were once common in the metalworking industries, but bandsaws and cold saws have mostly displaced them.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Many workshops in residential garages or basements and in light industry contain small or medium-sized bandsaws that can cut wood, metal, or plastic.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Often a general-purpose blade is left in place, although blades optimized for wood or metal can be switched out when volume of use warrants.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Most residential and commercial bandsaws are of the vertical type mounted on a bench or a cabinet stand.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Portable power tool versions, including cordless models, are also common in recent decades, allowing building contractors to bring them along on the truck to the jobsite.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Saws for cutting meat are typically of all stainless steel construction with easy to clean features.
[src:casting/bandsaw] The blades either have fine teeth with heat treated tips, or have plain or scalloped knife edges.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Bandsaws dedicated to industrial metal-cutting use, such as for structural steel in fabrication shops and for bar stock in machine shops, are available in vertical and horizontal designs.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Typical band speeds range from 40 ft/min (0.20 m/s) to 5,000 ft/min (25 m/s), although specialized bandsaws are built for friction cutting of hard metals and run band speeds of 15,000 ft/min (76 m/s).
[src:casting/bandsaw] Metal-cutting bandsaws are usually equipped with brushes or brushwheels to prevent chips from becoming stuck in between the blade's teeth.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Systems which cool the blade with cutting fluid are also common equipment on metal-cutting bandsaws.
[src:casting/bandsaw] The coolant washes away swarf and keeps the blade cool and lubricated.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Horizontal bandsaws hold the workpiece stationary while the blade swings down through the cut.
[src:casting/bandsaw] This configuration is used to cut long materials such as pipe or bar stock to length.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Thus it is an important part of the facilities in most machine shops.
[src:casting/bandsaw] The horizontal design is not useful for cutting curves or complicated shapes.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Small horizontal bandsaws typically employ a gravity feed alone, retarded to an adjustable degree by a coil spring; on industrial models, the rate of descent is usually controlled by a hydraulic cylinder that bleeds through an adjustable valve.
[src:casting/bandsaw] When the saw is set up for a cut, the operator raises the saw, positions the material to be cut underneath the blade, and then turns on the saw.
[src:casting/bandsaw] The blade slowly descends into the material, cutting it as the band blade moves.
[src:casting/bandsaw] When the cut is complete, a switch is tripped and the saw automatically turns off.
[src:casting/bandsaw] More sophisticated versions of this type of saw are partially or entirely automated (via PLC or CNC) for high-volume cutting of machining blanks.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Such machines provide a stream of cutting fluid recirculated from a sump, in the same manner that a CNC machining center does.
[src:casting/bandsaw] A vertical bandsaw, also called a contour saw, keeps the blade's path stationary while the workpiece is moved across it.
[src:casting/bandsaw] This type of saw can be used to cut out complex shapes and angles.
[src:casting/bandsaw] The part may be fed into the blade manually or with a power assist mechanism.
[src:casting/bandsaw] This type of metal-cutting bandsaw is often equipped with a built-in blade welder.
[src:casting/bandsaw] This not only allows the operator to repair broken blades or fabricate new blades quickly, but also allows for the blade to be purposely cut, routed through the center of a part, and re-welded in order to make interior cuts.
[src:casting/bandsaw] These saws are often fitted with a built-in air blower to cool the blade and to blow chips away from the cut area giving the operator a clear view of the work.
[src:casting/bandsaw] This type of saw is also built in a woodworking version.
[src:casting/bandsaw] The woodworking type is generally of much lighter construction and does not incorporate a power feed mechanism, coolant, or welder.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Advancements have also been made in the bandsaw blades used to cut metals.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Bimetal blades with high speed steel teeth, including cobalt grades, are now the norm.
[src:casting/bandsaw] The development of new tooth geometries and tooth pitches has produced increased production rates and greater blade life.
[src:casting/bandsaw] New materials and processes such as M51 steel and the cryogenic treatment of blades have produced results that were thought impossible just a few years ago.
[src:casting/bandsaw] New machines have been developed to automate the welding process of bandsaw blades as well.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Timber mills use very large bandsaws for ripping lumber; they are preferred over circular saws for ripping because they can accommodate large-diameter timber and because of their smaller kerf (cut size), resulting in less waste.
[src:casting/bandsaw] There are also small portable sawmills consisting of a somewhat smaller bandsaw mounted on a guiding table, which are called bandsaw mills (band saw mills, band sawmills).
[src:casting/bandsaw] Like chain saw mills (a chainsaw on a guiding table), they can be used inexpensively by one or two people out in the field.
[src:casting/bandsaw] These tools may be used by off-gridders and those doing small scale lumber processing in remote areas.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Today, even these mills may be powered by electricity.
[src:casting/bandsaw] In a full-size sawmill, the blades are mounted on wheels with a diameter large enough not to cause metal fatigue due to flexing when the blade repeatedly changes from a circular to a straight profile.
[src:casting/bandsaw] It is stretched very tight (with fatigue strength of the saw metal being the limiting factor).
[src:casting/bandsaw] Bandsaws of this size need to have a deformation worked into them that counteracts the forces and heating of operation.
[src:casting/bandsaw] They also need to be removed and serviced at regular intervals.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Sawfilers or sawdoctors are the craftsmen responsible for this work.
[src:casting/bandsaw] The shape of the tooth gullet is highly optimized and designed by the sawyer and sawfiler.
[src:casting/bandsaw] It varies according to the mill, as well as the type and condition of the wood.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Frozen logs often require a "frost notch" ground into the gullet to break the chips.
[src:casting/bandsaw] The shape of the tooth gullet is created when the blade is manufactured and its shape is automatically maintained with each sharpening.
[src:casting/bandsaw] The sawfiler will need to maintain the grinding wheel's profile with periodic dressing of the wheel.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Proper tracking of the blade is crucial to accurate cutting and considerably reduces blade breakage.
[src:casting/bandsaw] The first step to ensuring good tracking is to check that the two bandwheels or flywheels are co-planar.
[src:casting/bandsaw] This can be done by placing a straightedge across the front of the wheels and adjusting until each wheel touches on both its top and bottom.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Rotate the wheels with the blade in position and properly tensioned and check that the tracking is correct.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Now install the blade guide rollers and leave a gap of about 1mm between the back of the blade and the guide flange.
[src:casting/bandsaw] The teeth of blades that have become narrow through repeated sharpening will foul the front edge of the guide rollers due to their kerf set and force the blade out of alignment.
[src:casting/bandsaw] This can be remedied by cutting of a small step on the rollers' front edges to accommodate the protruding teeth.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Ideally the rollers should be crowned, (see belt and pulley systems) a configuration that assists in the proper tracking of bands and belts, at the same time allowing clearance for the set of the teeth.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Head saws are large bandsaws that make the initial cuts in a log.
[src:casting/bandsaw] They generally have a 2 to 3 in (51 to 76 mm) tooth space on the cutting edge and *sliver teeth* on the back.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Sliver teeth are non-cutting teeth designed to wipe slivers out of the way when the blade needs to back out of a cut.
[src:casting/bandsaw] A resaw is a large bandsaw optimized for cutting timber along the grain to reduce larger sections into smaller sections or veneers.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Resawing veneers requires a wide blade—commonly 2 to 3 in (51 to 76 mm)—with a small kerf to minimize waste.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Resaw blades of up to 1 in (25 mm) may be fitted to a standard bandsaw.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Double cut saws have cutting teeth on both sides.
[src:casting/bandsaw] They are generally very large, similar in size to a head saw.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Automatic bandsaws feature preset feed rate, return, fall, part feeding, and part clamping.
[src:casting/bandsaw] These are used in production environments where having a machine operator per saw is not practical.
[src:casting/bandsaw] One operator can feed and unload many automatic saws.
[src:casting/bandsaw] Some automatic saws rely on numerical control to not only cut faster, but to be more precise and perform more complex miter cuts.
[src:casting/bandsaw] At least two teeth must be in contact with the workpiece at all times to avoid stripping off the teeth.
[src:casting/casting] Throughout history, metal casting has been used to make tools, weapons, and religious objects.
[src:casting/casting] Metal casting history and development can be traced back to Southern Asia (China, India, etc).
[src:casting/casting] Southern Asian traditions and religions relied heavily on statue and relic castings.
[src:casting/casting] These items were frequently made from a copper alloy laced with lead.
[src:casting/casting] Since the beginning of metallurgy the majority of castings were simple one- to two-piece molds fashioned from either stone or ceramics.
[src:casting/casting] However, there is evidence of lost wax castings in numerous ancient civilizations.
[src:casting/casting] The lost wax process originated in ancient Mesopotamia (modern-day Iraq).
[src:casting/casting] The earliest known record of lost-wax casting is a clay tablet written in cuneiform in the ancient city of Sparta, Babylon (modern-day Iraq), which specifically records how much wax is needed to cast a key.
[src:casting/casting] The earliest-known castings in the global archaeological record were made in open stone molds.
[src:casting/casting] There are two types of lost wax methods: direct lost wax method and indirect lost wax method.
[src:casting/casting] The direct molding method is to make the wax material into the same wax mold as the casting by hand or other tools; the indirect molding method is to make the wax mold through the mold.
[src:casting/casting] The direct molding method requires craftsmen to have a high technical level; otherwise, the quality of castings cannot be guaranteed.
[src:casting/casting] However, the limitation of manual direct molding is that its efficiency is too low to achieve mass production.
[src:casting/casting] In this regard, indirect moulding has advantages.
[src:casting/casting] In indirect moulding, artisans usually make moulds from stone, wood, clay or other plastic materials.
[src:casting/casting] Early civilizations discovered lead aided in the fluidity of molten copper, allowing them to cast more intricate designs.
[src:casting/casting] For example, the dancing girl of Mohenjo-daro is a copper alloy casting that most likely utilizes the lost wax technique.
[src:casting/casting] Lost wax casting can be dated back to 4000 BC or the Chalcolithic period.
[src:casting/casting] One of the oldest studied examples of this technique is a 6,000-year-old amulet from the Indus Valley Civilisation.
[src:casting/casting] India is attributed as one of the first civilizations to use casting methods to mass-produce coins.
[src:casting/casting] Around the middle of the first millennium BC (1000 BC – 1 BC), coins used were made from silver, but as the millennium progressed, the coins shifted to a cast copper alloy.
[src:casting/casting] New technology was developed to mass-produce the new copper coins.
[src:casting/casting] Introduced was a multi-piece, stackable coin template mold.
[src:casting/casting] Multiple molds were placed on top of one another into a clay cylinder so molten metal could be poured down the center, filling and solidifying in the open spaces.
[src:casting/casting] This process allowed one hundred coins to be produced simultaneously.
[src:casting/casting] In the Middle East and West Africa, the lost wax technique was used very early in their metallurgy traditions, while China adopted it much later.
[src:casting/casting] In Western Europe lost wax techniques are considered to have been hardly used especially in comparison to that of the Indus Valley Civilisation.
[src:casting/casting] There were no pieces of lost wax found in the capital of Anyang during the Shang dynasty (1600–1040 BC) while a large amount (100,000 pieces) of piece-mould fragments were found.
[src:casting/casting] This led to the conclusion that lost wax was not performed in the capital during this dynasty.
[src:casting/casting] However, the discovery of a mask made using the investment moulding dated at around 1300 BC indicated that the lost wax technique may have influenced other regions in China.
[src:casting/casting] Historians debate the origin of the development of the cannon, but most evidence points to Turkey and Central Asia in the 18th and 19th century.
[src:casting/casting] The casting process of a cannon is a bit more complex with the use of a clay core, a template which has clay moulded around it and then broken out, followed by an assembly in a casting pit that involves binding the casting with iron bands.
[src:casting/casting] In metalworking, metal is heated until it becomes liquid and is then poured into a mold.
[src:casting/casting] The mold is a hollow cavity that includes the desired shape, but the mold also includes runners and risers that enable the metal to fill the mold.
[src:casting/casting] The mold and the metal are then cooled until the metal solidifies.
[src:casting/casting] The solidified part (the casting) is then recovered from the mold.
[src:casting/casting] Subsequent operations remove excess material caused by the casting process (such as the runners and risers).
[src:casting/casting] Plaster and other chemical curing materials, such as concrete and plastic resin, may be cast using single-use *waste* molds as noted above, multiple-use 'piece' molds, or molds made of small rigid pieces or of flexible material such as latex rubber (which is in turn supported by an exterior mold).
[src:casting/casting] When casting plaster or concrete, the material surface is flat and lacks transparency.
[src:casting/casting] Often topical treatments are applied to the surface.
[src:casting/casting] For example, painting and etching can be used in a way that gives the appearance of metal or stone.
[src:casting/casting] Alternatively, the material is altered in its initial casting process and may contain colored sand so as to give an appearance of stone.
[src:casting/casting] By casting concrete, rather than plaster, it is possible to create sculptures, fountains, or seating for outdoor use.
[src:casting/casting] A simulation of high-quality marble may be made using certain chemically-set plastic resins (for example, epoxy or polyester, which are thermosetting polymers) with powdered stone added for coloration, often with multiple colors worked in.
[src:casting/casting] The latter is a common means of making washstands, washstand tops and shower stalls, with the skilled working of multiple colors resulting in simulated staining patterns as is often found in natural marble or travertine.
[src:casting/casting] Raw castings often contain irregularities caused by seams and imperfections in the molds, as well as access ports for pouring material into the molds.
[src:casting/casting] The process of cutting, grinding, shaving or sanding away these unwanted bits is called "fettling" in British English.
[src:casting/casting] In modern times robotic processes have been developed to perform some of the more repetitive parts of the fettling process, but historically fettlers carried out this arduous work manually, and often in conditions dangerous to their health.
[src:casting/casting] Fettling can add significantly to the cost of the resulting product, and designers of molds seek to minimize it through the shape of the mold, the material being cast, and sometimes by including decorative elements.
[src:casting/casting] Casting process simulation uses numerical methods to calculate cast component quality considering mold filling, solidification and cooling, and provides a quantitative prediction of casting mechanical properties, thermal stresses and distortion.
[src:casting/casting] Simulation accurately describes a cast component's quality up-front before production starts.
[src:casting/casting] The casting rigging can be designed with respect to the required component properties.
[src:casting/casting] This has benefits beyond a reduction in pre-production sampling, as the precise layout of the complete casting system also leads to energy, material, and tooling savings.
[src:casting/casting] The software supports the user in component design, the determination of melting practice and casting methoding through to pattern and mold making, heat treatment, and finishing.
[src:casting/casting] This saves costs along the entire casting manufacturing route.
[src:casting/casting] Casting process simulation was initially developed at universities starting from the early '70s, mainly in Europe and in the U.S., and is regarded as the most important innovation in casting technology over the last 50 years.
[src:casting/casting] Since the late '80s, commercial programs (such as PoligonSoft, AutoCAST and Magma) are available which make it possible for foundries to gain new insight into what is happening inside the mold or die during the casting process.
